      <p class="kicker">The Guide &middot; Act Two</p>
      <h1>Act Two: the deed</h1>
      <p class="lede prose">
        The murder that the whole play has been circling finally happens, and Shakespeare refuses
        to let us watch it. Act Two is the act of the thing done: a killing hidden off-stage, a
        pair of ruined minds, a night that will not end, and a knocking at the gate that no amount
        of washing can answer.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0;">What happens</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene One (the court of Macbeth&rsquo;s castle, after midnight).</strong> Banquo
        cannot sleep and walks with his son Fleance, admitting the witches have been on his mind.
        Macbeth crosses him in the dark, and the two exchange careful, mistrustful words about the
        prophecy before Banquo retires. Alone, Macbeth sees a dagger hanging in the air, its handle
        turned towards his hand and its blade pointing him to Duncan&rsquo;s room. A bell sounds,
        his wife&rsquo;s signal that the way is clear, and he goes up to kill the king.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene Two (the same, moments later).</strong> Lady Macbeth waits below, having
        drugged the grooms and steadied her nerve. Macbeth returns with bloodied hands and a mind
        already coming apart, certain he heard a voice condemn him never to sleep again. He has
        carried the daggers out of the chamber and cannot make himself go back, so she takes them
        from him to smear the sleeping guards. A knocking starts at the gate. She insists a little
        water will wash the evidence, and the blame, away; he only wishes the noise could wake the
        man he has just killed.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene Three (the same, towards morning).</strong> A drunken Porter, dawdling to the
        gate, plays at being the doorkeeper of hell and jokes about drink and equivocation before
        letting in Macduff and Lennox. Macduff goes to rouse the king and comes back appalled: Duncan
        has been murdered. In the uproar Macbeth kills the two grooms, claiming his fury overtook him,
        and Lady Macbeth faints, whether truly or for effect. Sensing the danger to themselves,
        Duncan&rsquo;s sons Malcolm and Donalbain slip away, and their flight makes them look guilty.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene Four (outside the castle).</strong> An Old Man and Ross trade reports of a world
        gone wrong: darkness where daylight should be, a falcon killed by a lesser bird, Duncan&rsquo;s
        own horses turning savage. Macduff brings the news that suspicion has settled on the fled
        princes and that Macbeth has already been named king and gone to Scone for his crowning.
        Pointedly, Macduff will not go with him.
      </p>

      <h2>A closer look</h2>

      <h3>Off-stage violence: the murder we are not allowed to see</h3>
      <p>
        The most important staging decision in Act Two is a refusal. The murder of Duncan, the event
        the entire play is organised around, happens where we cannot see it, behind a door, in the
        gap between Scene One and Scene Two. Shakespeare hands the killing to our imaginations, and an
        imagined horror is always worse than a shown one, because the audience has to build it from its
        own fears. This is off-stage violence used deliberately: the same instinct that made
        &lsquo;present fears&rsquo; smaller than &lsquo;horrible imaginings&rsquo; back in Act One now
        shapes the theatre itself.
      </p>
      <p>
        The refusal also lets the structure carry the meaning. Scene Two is not the murder but its
        aftermath, and Shakespeare writes it in short, broken, overlapping lines, questions snatched
        back and forth in the dark, so that the verse itself sounds like two people who can barely
        breathe. Then the act widens in stages: from the hallucinated dagger of one man, to the two
        conspirators alone, to the Porter&rsquo;s coarse prose flinging the gate open, to the whole
        household in uproar, to the countryside itself reporting omens in Scene Four. The act moves
        from a private crime to a cracked cosmos, and that widening shape is the argument that killing
        a king is not a private act at all. Notice too the switch from verse to prose when the Porter
        speaks: the murder of the king literally breaks the play&rsquo;s language, dropping it from
        poetry into drunken prose at the very threshold of the crime.
      </p>

      <h3>The dagger and the hallucinating mind</h3>
      <p>
        &lsquo;Is this a dagger which I see before me&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 1) opens the soliloquy that
        defines Macbeth&rsquo;s tragedy: not a man who feels too little, but one who feels and imagines
        far too much. The dagger is a rhetorical question he cannot answer, an object that may be a real
        blade offered by fate or, as he half-realises, &lsquo;a dagger of the mind, a false creation&rsquo;
        (Act 2, Scene 1) thrown up by his own overheated brain. Shakespeare keeps the vision ambiguous on
        purpose. If it is supernatural, the murder is being guided from outside; if it is delusion, the
        rot is already inside Macbeth before he has spilt a drop of blood. The scene will not let us, or
        him, decide, and that uncertainty is the point.
      </p>
      <p>
        What the dagger begins, the murder completes. Macbeth returns in Scene Two unable to say the word
        for what he has done, reaching instead for the flat euphemism &lsquo;I have done the deed&rsquo;
        (Act 2, Scene 2), the monosyllables landing like something too heavy to hold. His guilt then
        detonates into hyperbole: &lsquo;Will all great Neptune&rsquo;s ocean wash this blood clean from
        my hand&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 2) turns a domestic act of hand-washing into a cosmic impossibility,
        an entire sea insufficient to the stain. The imagination that conjured a dagger from nothing now
        conjures a guilt bigger than the world, and it is this same restless mind, not the blood on his
        hands, that will keep him from sleep for the rest of the play.
      </p>

      <h3>Sound, sleep and the Porter&rsquo;s knocking</h3>
      <p>
        Act Two is Shakespeare&rsquo;s most sonic act, and its sounds are all wrong. First there is silence
        and the ringing bell that calls Macbeth to murder. Then there is the voice Macbeth thinks he hears,
        crying that &lsquo;Macbeth does murder sleep&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 2), a personification that makes
        sleep, the emblem of innocence and rest, into a victim of the crime. To murder sleep is to murder
        peace of mind, and the play is precise about the punishment: the man who kills the sleeping king
        will never sleep soundly again.
      </p>
      <p>
        Over the top of this comes the knocking, one of the great uses of sound in English drama. It begins
        while the Macbeths still have blood on their hands, and every knock is the outside world demanding
        to be let into the sealed room of their crime. Against that mounting dread Shakespeare sets, of all
        things, comedy: the drunken Porter, in prose, imagining himself the keeper of hell-gate. The jolt is
        deliberate. His joke that drink &lsquo;provokes the desire, but it takes away the performance&rsquo;
        (Act 2, Scene 3) keeps alive the play&rsquo;s obsession with equivocation and with the gap between
        wanting a thing and doing it, and his hell-gate fantasy tells the audience exactly where they are:
        the Macbeths&rsquo; castle has become the mouth of hell, and the knocking is the world of judgement
        arriving at the door. Lady Macbeth&rsquo;s brisk &lsquo;a little water clears us of this deed&rsquo;
        (Act 2, Scene 2) sounds, against all this noise, like a woman who has not yet heard what her husband
        has already understood.
      </p>

      <h2>Key quotations</h2>
      <table class="quote-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Quotation</th><th>Method</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;Is this a dagger which I see before me&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 1)</td>
            <td class="m">Rhetorical question, hallucination</td>
            <td>Opens the soliloquy of a man ruled by his imagination; leaves it open whether fate guides him or his own mind deceives him.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;A dagger of the mind, a false creation&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 1)</td>
            <td class="m">Metaphor, self-diagnosis</td>
            <td>Macbeth half-knows the vision is delusion, locating the corruption inside himself before the murder is even done.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;I have done the deed&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 2)</td>
            <td class="m">Euphemism, monosyllables</td>
            <td>He cannot name the murder; the flat, heavy monosyllables enact a guilt too great to be spoken plainly.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;Macbeth does murder sleep&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 2)</td>
            <td class="m">Personification</td>
            <td>Sleep becomes a murdered innocent; the crime destroys peace of mind, and names the insomnia that will punish him.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;Will all great Neptune&rsquo;s ocean wash this blood clean from my hand&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 2)</td>
            <td class="m">Hyperbole, rhetorical question</td>
            <td>Guilt swells to cosmic scale; a whole sea cannot cleanse him, and the stain is moral, not physical.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;A little water clears us of this deed&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 2)</td>
            <td class="m">Antithesis, dramatic irony</td>
            <td>Set directly against Neptune&rsquo;s ocean; her cool practicality is the irony the play will later demolish when she cannot wash the stain out.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;It provokes the desire, but it takes away the performance&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 3)</td>
            <td class="m">Prose, bawdy comedy, equivocation</td>
            <td>The Porter&rsquo;s joke keeps the theme of equivocation alive and drops the play into prose at the threshold of the crime, easing and sharpening the dread.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;&rsquo;Tis unnatural, even like the deed that&rsquo;s done&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 4)</td>
            <td class="m">Pathetic fallacy, natural order</td>
            <td>The murder of a king disorders the whole of nature; the omens argue that regicide is a crime against the cosmic chain, not just against a man.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="box think">
        <h3>Think it through</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Why does Shakespeare keep the murder off-stage? What would be lost if we watched Macbeth kill Duncan?</li>
          <li>Is the dagger real, supernatural or a symptom of Macbeth&rsquo;s mind, and does it change the meaning of the play depending on which you choose?</li>
          <li>The Porter scene is comic and arrives at the darkest moment. Is the comedy a release, an intensifier, or both, and what does the hell-gate joke tell the audience?</li>
          <li>In Scene Two, Lady Macbeth is composed and Macbeth is falling apart. How does that reversal complicate the idea that she is the ruthless one?</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="box exam">
        <h3>Towards the coursework</h3>
        <p>
          Act Two hands each set question its sharpest material. On <strong>kingship</strong>, the omens of
          Scene Four make regicide a wound in nature itself, which lets you argue that the play treats a king
          as the keystone of cosmic order rather than merely a powerful man. On the <strong>presentation of
          women</strong>, put Lady Macbeth&rsquo;s &lsquo;a little water clears us of this deed&rsquo; beside
          Macbeth&rsquo;s Neptune&rsquo;s-ocean panic and ask whether her control is strength or denial, since
          the play will later reverse them completely. On <strong>masculinity</strong>, notice that the man
          who was all soldierly nerve in Act One is now the one unmanned by conscience, so that the act quietly
          questions what courage and manhood actually are. Your task now: take the contrast between &lsquo;a
          little water clears us of this deed&rsquo; and &lsquo;will all great Neptune&rsquo;s ocean wash this
          blood clean from my hand&rsquo; and write a short paragraph, one method, one effect, one argued claim,
          on how Shakespeare uses the two washing images to divide the couple. Then carry that paragraph forward
          to the <a href="/coursework/">coursework page</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

